<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920319-0075</DOCNO><DOCID>920319-0075.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Keating Exercises   Right Not to Answer   Plaintiffs' Questions</HL><DATE>03/19/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   X-AMC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY (BCY)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</NS><RE>ARIZONA (AZ)CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   TUCSON, Ariz. -- Charles H. Keating Jr. repeatedly invokedhis Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination whencalled to defend himself against charges he and his companiestricked thousands of people into buying risky bonds sold byLincoln Savings andamp; Loan Association.   As expected, Mr. Keating, the former chairman of AmericanContinental Corp., of Phoenix, refused to answer questions ina $1.2 billion federal trial here. He said his attorneysadvised him not to testify because of his pending federalcriminal trial in Los Angeles. &quot;Until I am able to testify,&quot;Mr. Keating said, &quot;the truth will not be heard.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   The civil trial here, which began last Friday, encompassestwo class-action lawsuits on behalf of more than 20,000investors who lost about $250 million in the 1989 collapse ofLincoln, Irvine, Calif.   Keating faces sentencing April 10 in a California statecourt on a fraud conviction in connection with the bondsales.</TEXT></DOC>